            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sarah Abramson\u2019s story is woven into the fabric of two Californias. Raised in a pragmatic, middle-class Sacramento suburb by a teacher and a small business owner, she felt a pull towards the complex human tapestry of the city she saw on the news. This led her to San Francisco State University in the late 1980s, where a degree in Social Work felt less like a choice and more like a calling.\n\nHer early career was a trial by fire. As a frontline case manager in the Tenderloin, she worked with unhoused populations and at-risk youth, learning the grit and resilience required to navigate systemic failures. The dot-com boom of the late 90s became her professional turning point. While the city buzzed with tech wealth, she witnessed the \"digital divide\" become a chasm, locking her clients out of essential services, job applications, and healthcare information that were rapidly moving online. This wasn't a problem she could solve one case at a time.\n\nMotivated by this new form of inequity, Sarah transitioned from direct service to program development. She learned grant writing and management on the job, slowly building a reputation for creating effective, community-focused initiatives. Now, as the Program Director for a non-profit dedicated to digital health equity, she channels her frontline experience into building systemic solutions. She manages programs that provide seniors with tablets and training, and partners with clinics to develop multilingual health apps.\n\nToday, Sarah lives in a cozy, rent-controlled apartment in Noe Valley. Divorced amicably a decade ago, she finds companionship in a close-knit circle of friends and her rescue golden retriever, Cody. Her daily routine is grounded: an early morning walk with Cody at Douglass Park, followed by a 3.8-mile ride on the J-Church Muni line to her SoMa office. Evenings are for simple pleasures\u2014cooking, reading, or attending a neighborhood meeting.\n\nHer ambition is no longer about saving the world, but about building sustainable systems. She hopes to see her programs become a national model and dreams of mentoring the next generation of social innovators. Sarah Abramson is a quintessential San Franciscan: not a tech titan, but a dedicated builder who has spent her life trying to ensure the city\u2019s progress leaves no one behind."
