            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nOctober 1989. She was in her SF State dorm when the world began to liquefy. After the violent shaking stopped, the fear was quickly replaced by a strange, shared adrenaline. In the following days, she wasn't a student from Sacramento anymore; she was part of a city checking on neighbors, sharing batteries, and pulling together. That raw, spontaneous community care was the moment her theoretical social work degree became a visceral, undeniable calling. It was the San Francisco she had come to find, revealed in rubble and resilience.\n\n2.\nMid-1990s. She remembers the fragile pride in a teenager\u2019s eyes in the Tenderloin the day she helped him get his first library card. It felt like a victory. A few months later, she heard he was back on the streets. The small triumph curdled into a hard lesson: a library card couldn't fix a broken system. It was this moment of painful clarity that first planted the seed of moving beyond one-on-one casework, forcing her to look for bigger, more structural solutions to the city's deep-rooted inequities.\n\n3.\nLate 1990s. An elderly client, Maria, sat before her, clutching a newspaper clipping for a janitorial job. The application was \u201conline only.\u201d Sarah watched Maria\u2019s hope collapse into confusion and shame, and felt a profound sense of failure. She had resources for food and shelter, but not for this new, invisible wall. In that fluorescent-lit office, her life's mission pivoted from managing individual crises to dismantling the digital barriers that were beginning to create them on a massive scale.\n\n4.\nEarly 2014. The first year after the divorce, the silence in her Noe Valley apartment was cavernous. Then came Cody. She remembers the drive home from the shelter, his warm weight in the passenger seat. That first night, he padded over and rested his heavy golden head on her lap as she read on the sofa. In that quiet, trusting gesture, the apartment wasn't empty anymore. It was home. Her home. Entirely and peacefully hers, filled with a new, simpler kind of love.\n\n5.\nJust last year, during a site visit, she watched Mrs. Chen, a recipient of one of her program's tablets, laugh with delight. For the first time, Mrs. Chen was seeing her newborn great-grandchild in another state via a video call. Sarah stood back, unseen, witnessing the connection she'd helped forge. It wasn't the thrill of a grant approval or a big speech. It was quiet, profound, and real. This was the system working\u2014not for efficiency, but for joy. This was why she did it."
